[h2 id=AdjustTheAvisynthScript 
	" Adjust the AviSynth script
	$LF
]h2
[div class=p 
	"Open 
	[b 
		"encode.avs
	]b
	" in 
	[b 
		"Notepad++
	]b
	", it's a text file, so you can edit it. Make sure to keep the AVS script, the BAT script, logo and movie files in the same folder. All other dependencies lie in specific folders of the package.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Preview is done by drag'n'dropping the AVS script into 
	[b 
		"VirtualDub
	]b
	" window, to pick frame numbers from the encode and to adjust the subtitles (and also to check if all is working as you wish). Each time you edit the script, save it in 
	[b 
		"Notepad++
	]b
	" and press 
	[b 
		"F2
	]b
	" in 
	[b 
		"VirtualDub
	]b
	" to reload the updated source file.
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" If you don't have the 
		[a href=https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=48145 rel=noopener external nofollow 
			"Visual C++ Redistributable
		]a
		" installed, one of the scripts won't load.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h3 id=MultipleSegments 
	" Multiple segments
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"If the dump is too huge, you will get several AVI files split near 2GB. If there are only few of them, you can import them as a single command:
	$LF
]div
[pre 
	[code class=language-avs 
		$UNPRINTABLE TEXT!!!
	]code
]pre
[div class=p 
	"But if the amount of segments is big, it's not useful to do the above. For that, we have the 
	[b 
		"AppendSegment()
	]b
	" function. 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=Here's a post|href=/Forum/Posts/462891)
	" describing how to use it.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=MovieLength 
	" Movie length
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"As you preview your encode in 
	[b 
		"VirtualDub
	]b
	", navigate to the movie ending. The idea is to present all contents of the game in the encode, but keep it as small as possible.
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" If the game restarts, select the frame right before restart
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" If the music stops playing at some point, where nothing new is shown visually, pick the frame when it stops playing.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" If the music loops, and the picture does not change, find the frame when the first full loop ends
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"Copy the framenumber and paste it as the "trimframe" value. The script assumes you are using the preview to figure out the trimframe, and automatically subtracts the logo length.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=Subtitles 
	" Subtitles
	$LF
]h3
[h4 id=MovieInfo 
	" Movie info
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Go to the submission page and copy/paste into the corresponding script strings:
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" The game name
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The branch name, if applicable (paste inside 'such quotes', so that the result looks like that "'branch'")
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The Author's name
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The completion time
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The rerecord count
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"If the rerecord count is broken, showing an unfairly low number, write "unknown".
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"Always double-check the game names put into submissions. Always apply 
			(__wikiLink|displaytext=our standards|href=/PublisherGuidelines#GameName)
			" to them.
		]b
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 id=TimingAndPlacement 
	" Timing and placement
	$LF
]h4
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"subFF
		]b
		" is the first frame for subtitles. Use the first frame of the first level for that (after the fade-in ends), whenever they don't cover important game elements (in particular, the player character), when a countdown has ended (usually on "Go!") or whenever they are 
		[em 
			"not
		]em
		" visible during fade transitions for the entire duration.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"subEntry
		]b
		" is how many subtitle entries (from 2 up to 4) are going to be present in the encode.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"subYpc
		]b
		" is in how many percent of the video height to shift the subtitles down by. Use 0 to have them on top, other positions must be figured out at previews.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"subAlign
		]b
		" gives the alignment relative to the encode width (which is automated depending on which align you use). 8 aligns to the center, 7 - to the left, 9 - to the right.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"subXpc
		]b
		" is used when you need to push the subtitles away from the screen edge. Leave 0 if you align at the center.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"subFF2delay
		]b
		", 
		[b 
			"subFF2delay2
		]b
		" and 
		[b 
			"subFF2delay3
		]b
		" are used when you need to have a delay between subtitle entries.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"Always make sure that your subtitles don't cover any important in-game elements, action, overscan area or internal game borders (avoiding screen transitions is also a good habit). Adjust the timing and position if you have to. If unsure, ask in tasvideos chats (IRC or Discord), or send a private message to a Senior Publisher.
		]b
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h3 id=LwlibavvideosourceForTrickyCodecs 
	" LWLibavVideoSource for tricky codecs
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"LWLibavVideoSource is a source filter (e.g. AviSource) for AviSynth from the 
	[a href=http://avisynth.nl/index.php/LSMASHSource rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"LSMASHSource
	]a
	" plugin collection.
	$LF
	[br 
	]br
	[b 
		"Pros:
	]b
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" Can decode anything that FFmpeg can, including sometimes-troublesome codecs like CamStudio and FFV1
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Doesn't care about bitness
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	[b 
		"Cons:
	]b
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" Harder to use
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Must build an index file
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Slower than an installed codec
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 id=HowToUse 
	" How to use
	$LF
]h4
[ol 
	[li 
		" Download LSMASHSource from the above link, and copy the 32- and 64- bit LSMASHSource.dll files to the appropriate plugin locations.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Instead of writing 
		[code 
			"AviSource("file.avi")
		]code
		" in your AviSynth script, you would write 
		[code 
			"LWLibavVideoSource("file.avi", fpsnum=60000, fpsden=1001, format="RGB24")
		]code
		".
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" You 
				[b 
					"must
				]b
				" supply accurate values for the 
				[code 
					"fpsnum
				]code
				" and 
				[code 
					"fpsden
				]code
				" parameters, or the filter will mess up the framerate. Check the dumped video's framerate and match it. For 59.94 fps NTSC video: 
				[code 
					"fpsnum=60000, fpsden=1001
				]code
				". For 60.099 fps SNES video: 
				[code 
					"fpsnum=60099, fpsden=1000
				]code
				". For 60 fps video: 
				[code 
					"fpsnum=60
				]code
				" (you can leave out 
				[code 
					"fpsden
				]code
				" and it will default to 1).
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" VirtualDub/FFmpeg/x264 don't like LWLibavVideoSource's default format, so you will always need to supply the 
				[code 
					"format
				]code
				" parameter. 
				[code 
					""RGB24"
				]code
				" is a good default to use as it will do a lossless, fast conversion.
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
	[li 
		" The first time an AVS script with a call to 
		[code 
			"LWLibavVideoSource
		]code
		" gets executed, it will generated an index file for the source video with the extension 
		[code 
			".lwi
		]code
		".
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" If the script is loaded for the first time in VirtualDub, you will not see any progress meter and the program will simply appear to hang while the file is being generated. This could take an hour or more for 4K video!
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" You can instead run your script for the first time with 
				[code 
					"ffprobe -hide_banner myscript.avs
				]code
				" and you will get a progress indicator while the file is built.
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
	[li 
		" Dub the source video's audio with 
		[code 
			"AudioDub( WavSource("file.avi") )
		]code
		" as LWLibavVideoSource does not read any audio data.
		$LF
	]li
]ol
[h4 id=Troubleshooting 
	" Troubleshooting
	$LF
]h4
[ul 
	[li 
		" This index file needs to stay with the source file or the filter will have to regenerate it each time.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" AviSynth seems to decide at random that it's time to rebuild the index file for no good reason. To avoid this, always make a backup copy of the 
		[code 
			".lwi
		]code
		" file immediately, and set the original to read-only.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The index doesn't seem to like being copied between computers. If you are getting an error message stating that the video track of the file could not found, you may need to let the index file get rebuilt on the new computer.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[hr 
]hr
[h2 id=RunGlobalBat 
	" Run global.bat
	$LF
]h2
[ul 
	[li 
		" Aspect ratio options
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" If you encode for a handheld console, type 
				[b 
					"1
				]b
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" If your console is intended for use with a CRT TV, type 
				[b 
					"2
				]b
				" (exception: 
				(__wikiLink|displaytext=Dolphin|href=/EncodingGuide/VideoDumping/Dolphin#AspectRatio)
				". Type 
				[b 
					"1
				]b
				" in this case.)
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" If your console is intended for use with an LCD TV, type 
				[b 
					"3
				]b
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" If you're encoding for a game that needs other aspect ratio (like multi-screen arcades), type 4 to enter the specific aspect ratio
				$LF
				[ul 
					[li 
						"Specifically for Amiga: Use a custom aspect ratio of 617:482 for NTSC and 1299:1000 for PAL (although no aspect ratio correction is also considered fine for PAL, in which case, type 
						[b 
							"1
						]b
						").
						$LF
					]li
				]ul
			]li
		]ul
	]li
	[li 
		" What encode do you want to do
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" Encode all in one flow (
				[b 
					"3
				]b
				") or choose a single method. Be ready to wait several hours for each encode.
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"After all is over, get your files in the 
	[b 
		"output
	]b
	" folder
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[del 
		$LF
	]del
]div
[h2 id=AddingCommentarySubtitles 
	" Adding commentary subtitles
	$LF
]h2
[div class=p 
	"In YouTube Studio:
	$LF
]div
[ol 
	[li 
		" Click on Details on the video you've uploaded, then on Subtitles below the video preview.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" From here, upload the SRT (that should account for the logo, if it doesn't, you can adjust it easily 
		[a href=https://subshifter.bitsnbites.eu rel=noopener external nofollow 
			"here
		]a
		" (simply shift the subtitles by the amount after the logo ends, usually around 2 seconds). It is a subtitles file with timing.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Click Save.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" On the Subtitles pane, click on the three dots, then click Rename.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Type in "Author's commentary" (or "Authors' commentary" if there are multiple authors.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Click on "Save".
		$LF
	]li
]ol
[div class=p 
	"In the downloadable encode:
	$LF
]div
[ol 
	[li 
		" Copy 
		[code 
			"global.bat
		]code
		" and rename the newly created copy 
		[code 
			"globalwithcommentary.bat
		]code
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Add 
		[code 
			"-add commentary.srt:lang=eng
		]code
		" on the muxing step of the downloadable (denoted as Archive 480p stream in the batch file) before 
		[code 
			"-new .\output\encode_480p.mp4
		]code
		".
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		"Encode as usual with the 
		[code 
			"globalwithcommentary
		]code
		" batch file.
		$LF
	]li
]ol
[div class=p 
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
]div
[div class=card border 
	[div class=card-body 
		[div class=h2 
			[div class=p 
				"Prepare all files
				$LF
			]div
		]div
	]div
]div
[div class=p 
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
]div
[h2 id=EncodeFileNames 
	" Encode file names
	$LF
]h2
[div class=p 
	[b 
		"gamenameregion-tasv#-branch-author_encodetype
	]b
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" The game name should be concise, use common abbreviations (
		[b 
			"smb
		]b
		" for Super Mario Bros.) and precedent when possible (
		[b 
			"chipdale
		]b
		" instead of 
		[b 
			"chipndale
		]b
		"). Required.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Add the region letter (
		[b 
			"j
		]b
		" or 
		[b 
			"e
		]b
		") if it is not USA (if USA version exists at all). Optional.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Use 
		[b 
			"-tas
		]b
		" if it's a speedrun, otherwise use 
		[b 
			"-playaround
		]b
		". Required.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" If it's not the first version of that game by the same author, add 
		[b 
			"v2
		]b
		" (or any other appropriate number), otherwise avoid. Optional.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Add the branch name only if it is not default. Note: when setting percentage, use 
		[b 
			"p
		]b
		" instead of 
		[b 
			"%
		]b
		". Optional.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Separate multiple authors names with a comma (,) or an underscore (_).
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Encode type is usually only needed if it's an alternate encode (e.g. camhack or slowed down encode)
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"If not sure about a token, investigate similar publications, how their files are named. Example:
	$LF
]div
[pre 
	"battletoadsj-tasv3-1player-feos
	$LF
]pre
[hr 
]hr
[h2 id=UploadToYoutube 
	" Upload to YouTube
	$LF
]h2
[div class=p 
	"Uploading to YouTube is done on YouTube itself. If you are an editor for TASVideosChannel, simply follow the following steps:
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"1) Switch over to TVC (Google Account profile pic -> Switch Accounts)
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
	"2) Click on Upload and drag-and-drop the YouTube encode.
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
	"3) Put in a title and, optionally, a description.
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
	"4) Click Next several times, then wait for it to be uploaded.
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
]div
[h2 id=UploadToArchiveOrg 
	" Upload to Archive.org
	$LF
]h2
[div class=p 
	"Upload 
	[b 
		"the downloadable 480p encode
	]b
	".
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" Go to 
		[a href=https://archive.org/upload/ rel=noopener external nofollow 
			"https://archive.org/upload/
		]a
		" and drag'n'drop the file you are about to upload onto the gray area.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The titles, as well as the item link, will be autofilled.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" In the 
		[b 
			"Description
		]b
		" field, provide the submission link
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"Subject Tags
		]b
		": some words from the submission page title, or just 
		[b 
			"tas
		]b
		".
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Select a specific collection from the pop-down list, if allowed: 
		[b 
			"Speed Runs
		]b
		".
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" You might also need to remove the 
		[b 
			"additional metadata
		]b
		".
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"Once all is done, press the 
	[b 
		"Upload and Create Your Item
	]b
	" button.
	$LF
]div
